You deserve what you get. When you’re a battered woman, who won't act to save her neck. From the chopping block of an abusive mans threat.

Constantly returning to the relationship. As if, your blood and tears are repaying some debt. Owed to a man who could justify his every action.

All while robbing you of your last breath. Beating you to within an inch of your life. As you wake up in the hospital.

And he's bedside, feigning regret. How stupid do you have to be. To not know that this cancer will spread.

For the children you give birth to, might as well be punching bags you bred. Your sins are now twice as damning.

Because you started the fucking thread. That will grow into a noose. When from an offense, you choose to turn your head.

Slowly tightening, with every year you force your children to live beneath the dread. You’re a long way from the victim he first met.

You’re a fucking accomplice. To a crime, you could have fled. Let this go out to all women who stay past the first punch to the head.

Pray that he fucking kills you. Before you give birth to children, who will be forced to continue your thread.

snippet.textDisplay: I grew up through my teens watching WCW and WWF so this is painfully nostalgic.... This is one hell of a documentary.  I'm simultaneously looking forward to and dreading the 2nd part I'm about to start.  I remember everyone I knew at school who were also wrestling fans were all shocked when the tragic news hit.  I couldn't wrap my head around it because Benoit was so stoic in the ring and to think there was so much more going on was too much for kids our age to really comprehend. I appreciate Vice letting the people who were closest to him give their accounts. So many documentaries in the past seem to try forcing everything to fit whatever narrative they had planned beforehand so props to Vice for putting in the work to give us first-hand, intimate details from those who really knew him.

snippet.textDisplay:
The whole Benoit situation is interesting in the sense that people have such a hard time trying to fathom both the good AND the bad in one person at the same time. It's almost like a maturity test: kids only see the world in black and white, and as we grow up we start to see shades of gray, multiple black/white situations, complex nuanced situations, and other things that aren't so simple.

The Benoit situation is especially tough, even for mature adults: very rarely is a person asked to put "good person" and "evil horrible murderer" in the same person at the same time

Personally, my way of coping is the "Superman" approach. Separate the person he was from the person he became by "Pre-Crisis" and "Post-Crisis" labels with the biggest Crisis (among many) being Eddie Guerrero's death.

Of course many people refuse to recognize one side at all. "He's a murderer" while completely dissociating everything else from reality, while at the same time, shaming people that do see the other side.

VICE's approach seems to acknowledge and recognize this by putting "Pre-Crisis" Benoit in Part 1 and "Post-Crisis" Benoit in Part 2.
